{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3373351,"name":"Domenico","username":"domidev","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/domidev/{size}/225499_2.png","created_at":"2024-04-25T15:54:25.560Z","cooked":"<p>In our robot’s codebase, we manage swerve drive strategies using a structured approach with abstract strategy classes and derived classes for both lateral and yaw movements. This modular design allows for easy switching between different driving strategies during a match, depending on the game scenario.</p>
<h4><a name="key-components-1" class="anchor" href="#key-components-1"></a>Key Components:</h4>
<ol>
<li><strong>Swerves Class</strong>: Manages the overall swerve modules, integrating both lateral and yaw strategies.</li>
<li><strong>Lateral and Yaw Strategy Classes</strong>: Define the interface and implementation for various driving strategies.</li>
</ol>
<p>Here’s a brief overview of how these are structured in our code:</p>
<p><strong>Swerves Class</strong>:<br>
This class initializes and manages swerve modules, handling the application of both lateral and yaw strategies based on game conditions.</p>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">// Sample snippet for managing swerve drive strategies
public void setFieldCentric(double vx, double vy) {
    this._lateralStrategyParameters = new FieldCentricStrategy.FieldCentricParameters(vx, vy);
    if (!isFieldCentric())
        setLateralStrategy(new FieldCentricStrategy());
}
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Lateral Strategies</strong>:<br>
These strategies define how the robot moves laterally (e.g., field-centric, robot-centric).</p>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">// Field Centric Strategy Example
public class FieldCentricStrategy extends PlanarCentricStrategy {
    @Override
    public Vector2d getLateralSpeeds(LateralStrategyParameters params) {
        FieldCentricParameters fieldParams = (FieldCentricParameters) params;
        PlanarCentricParameters planarParams = new PlanarCentricParameters(fieldParams.fieldRelativeSpeeds, new Rotation2d());
        return super.getLateralSpeeds(planarParams);
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Yaw Strategies</strong>:<br>
These strategies manage the robot’s orientation on the field.</p>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">// Omega Strategy for dynamic yaw adjustments
public class OmegaStrategy extends YawStrategy {
    @Override
    public Rotation2d getYawSpeed(YawStrategyParameters params) {
        OmegaStartegyParameters omegaParams = (OmegaStartegyParameters) params;
        return omegaParams.omega;
    }
}
</code></pre>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">// Lock the robot to an angle
public class FixedStrategy extends OmegaStrategy {
    public PIDController _yawPID = Constants.SwervesConstants.YawControl.kYawPID;

    public FixedStrategy() {
        this._yawPID.reset();
        this._yawPID.enableContinuousInput(-180, 180);
    }

    public static class FixedStrategyParameters extends YawStrategyParameters {
        public Rotation2d angle;

        public FixedStrategyParameters(Rotation2d angle) {
            this.angle = angle;
        }
    }

    public boolean isYawSetpointReached() {
        return Math.abs(getError()) &lt; Constants.SwervesConstants.YawControl.kSwervesYawTolerance.getDegrees();
    }

    public double getError() {
        return _yawPID.getPositionError();
    }

    @Override
    public Rotation2d getYawSpeed(YawStrategyParameters params) {
        FixedStrategyParameters fixedParams = (FixedStrategyParameters) params;
        Rotation2d vRot = Rotation2d.fromDegrees(0);
        vRot = Rotation2d
                .fromRadians(_yawPID.calculate(Localization.getInstance().getRobotPose().getRotation().getDegrees(),
                        fixedParams.angle.getDegrees())); // fromRadians is intentional
        vRot = isYawSetpointReached() ? Rotation2d.fromDegrees(0) : vRot;

        return vRot;
    }
}
</code></pre>
